    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-02-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-02-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="165"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d165">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/1490</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Denmark</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_EMF1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Egan</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Copenhagen</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-02-21">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 21, 1915</hi>.</date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received February 22, 9 a. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>140. German Admiralty firmly resolved to starve England. Reliably informed that
                    Germany has ready large supply new submarine boats. Is understood in Berlin
                    German Government will be implacable until United States ceases to send
                    munitions of war to the Allies.</p>
                <p>German Government considers American opinion unjust in supposing that Germany
                    wants more European territory. It would have American people understand that it
                    wishes only colonial expansion and the right to commercial progress.</p>
                <p>There is no question as to Germany’s not being able to put at least three million
                    more men in the field.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">American Minister</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
